commit.message:
Fix package metadata

The PyPI metadata parser got stricter, so it's time to clear up the
cargo...

- Let `Maintainer-email` be valid RFC-822 (comma-separated addresses)
- Do the same for the `Maintainer` fields
- Remove `Platform` as it is only needed for obscure ones not covered
  by the classifiers
- Remove `License` for the same reason
- Add a classifier for Development Status

Prepare for release 8.0.0

Update changelog and bump version number in setup.py.

Update documentation

Try to spell out the use cases for this package and also when one
should not need it, to counter all the ancient blog posts and
stackoverflows floating around. Mention that it was tested on Python
3.8 as well.

Xenial does not have Python2 <2.7 or Python3 <3.4

We've tested those successfully in build 63, so now it is time
to let them go.

Extend Travis and tox testing to Python 3.7+

It might still be necessary to cull older tests on the Xenial dist.

Update Python module code for 3.4 and 3.5

Introduce a separate Python 3.4 readline.c from GitHub 3.4 branch
(commit 7462b64 dated 2015-11-02, released as part of 3.4.4). This
avoids the Py_DecodeLocale function in the previous 3.5 version, which
has been removed again and reverted to the newer 3.6 version instead.
Please be happy, Travis!

Update Python module code for 3.4 and 3.5

Introduce a separate Python 3.5 readline.c from GitHub 3.5 branch
(commit 68c3724 dated 2017-07-09, released as part of 3.5.4), and
also let it stand in for 3.4. This still uses Py_DECREF instead of
Py_XSETREF, which was only introduced in 3.6.

Update Python module code for 3.4 to 3.6

Introduce a separate Python 3.6 readline.c from GitHub 3.6 branch
(commit 25555e0 dated 2018-12-08, released as part of 3.6.8), and also
let it stand in for 3.4 and 3.5. This avoids the _Py_SetLocaleFromEnv
function in the 3.x version, which was only introduced in 3.7.

Build against readline 8.0

There are no patches for this yet (released 7 Jan 2019). The main
improvements involve vi mode, inputrc config and multibyte characters.
Bump the package version number to an alpha release.

Update Python module code

Use Python 3.x readline.c from GitHub 3.7 branch (commit ef10f88 dated
2019-03-20, released as part of 3.7.3) and Python 2.x readline.c from
GitHub 2.7 branch (commit 89b5ea2 dated 2018-12-19, released as part of
2.7.16). The 3.7 version seems to be more up to date than the 3.8
version...

Also enable the HAVE_RL_RESIZE_TERMINAL macro in setup.py.

commit.message:
Suggest pip >= 8.0 in docs

This is the minimum version of pip that will install the MacPython
wheels for Python 2.7 on macOS (especially an issue for system Python).
Earlier versions fall back to the source package and the risk of
compiler issues.
Remove bold links in RST as GitHub doesn't like it

Prepare for release 6.3.8

Update changelog and bump version number in setup.py.

Update documentation

Finesse the release process and update the main docs to mention that
IPython does not need gnureadline anymore (and spell macOS correctly).

Update release process docs

This now focuses on the Travis tests and wheel production as opposed
to the old manual uploads.
Mild flake8 fixes
Attempt to test on Python 3.6
Ignore .cache directory produced by tox
Include Python 3.4 and 3.5 in automated tests

Guess the actual compiler from "cc -v"

This is simply to aid debugging. The guess works with Mavericks clang and
gcc 5.2 and hopefully others too.

Fix compilation with GNU gcc

For some obscure reason the (real) gcc compiler refuses to compile when
presented with the flags '-arch i386 -arch x86_64', instead of just picking the
last item as promised. See https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=60821
for more details.

This is fixed by detecting the scenario (multiple arches don't work and they
are i386 + x86_64, in that order) and then reverting to x86_64 only (or nothing
to trigger the default architecture).

This addresses issue #44.

Ensure that Python 3.3 module caters for 3.0, 3.1

Just in case someone still uses those.

Update Python module code

Use Python 3.x readline.c from hg 3.4 / 3.5 branch (changeset ID
95813:ec6ed10d611e) and Python 2.x readline.c from hg 2.7 branch
(changeset ID 95814:192f9efe4a38) while 3.2 / 3.3 module stays the
same. The updates include a fix for emitting ANSI 8-bit characters
to the terminal during initialisation, and a new feature for 3.x
that allows appending to the history file from multiple sessions.

Make Python 3.4+ the default Python 3

Instead of having a special case for Python 3.4, have one for 3.3 instead (and
point 3.2 at it too). This allows Python 3.4, 3.5 and up to share the same
module.

This change is done in two steps to simplify the tracking of the directory
renames.

Add special cases for Python 3.2 and 3.3

Instead of having a special case for Python 3.4, have one for 3.3 instead (and
point 3.2 at it too). This allows Python 3.4, 3.5 and up to share the same
module.
Build against readline 6.3 (patch-level 8)

Merge pull request #39 from seanmccully/fixes-shell-path

Fix use of bash in expected locations

Make GPLv3 license explicit

Since the Python module wraps and contains GNU readline which is GPLv3,
it makes sense to be GPLv3 too. It always has been, but this has now
been clarified by copying COPYING from readline 6.3 to LICENSE and
picking a more specific trove classifier in setup.py.

This closes issue #40.
